title: Solutions Architect
company: Systems Made Simple, A Lockheed Martin Company
description: My role is to support development of process and technology-based methodologies - such as Cloud-based Storage on Demand - for use in the Veteran’s Administration including prototyping, configuring and deployment model systems and workflows, i.e. "Utility Computing" using the SMS Innovation Lab. The Storage on Demand project will enable VA data-centers to position large amounts of storage platforms (fully populated) on the computer room floor and only be charged for assets utilized (on demand). I'm pursuing similar architecture defense and security solutions as well using IXIA Phantom tap, Fireeye, and Cyvision Cauldron in a cloud based context. The Storage on Demand architecture approach will align operational needs with procurement; will reduce capital expenditures; and will provide ready-for-use capacity in as little as 72 hours (a few hours in some cases). We also support vendor product analysis, lab deployment, documentation, configuration/programming and vendor screening. The SMS-VA innovation lab baseline is built using VMware ESX 5.5 and includes a Windows 2012 Server Domain Controller, Server 2k8 Active Directory server and VMware virtual desktops implemented using Windows 7 (but also some specialized Linux systems). We configure specialized enclaves to support hardware and software product analysis but also vulnerability analysis and penetration testing in support of VA ATO/IATO/C&A analysis activities (based on BT5 and/or Kali with Tenable Nessus on Windows) for SOD vendors (EMC - VIPER, NetApp InSight OnTap, Dell Compellent for example). I am fortunate to work with a great team with a broad range of skills.

title: Senior Principal Engineer
description: On USCYBERCOM, Ms Beltz helped to design and implement utilizing the SAS Suite of Software a Cyber Command Dashboard for monitoring threats. The dashboard will have the ability to fuse the numerous available sources of data to create a holistic view of a specific network asset (e.g., an IP address), threat (e.g., a computer virus), or other named entity. A set of automated processes would govern the flow of information into the command, shared use among USCYBERCOM’s internal organizations, and then out of the command to geographically distributed cyberspace centers and downstream customers. Ms. Beltz worked to extract tactical level information to address concern for the decision-makers at USCYBERCOM and made them available on the web-based dashboard. Ms. Beltz served as the Baseline Test Director and was responsible for managing the test team, preparing Test & Evaluation Strategies (TES), analyzing test data, developing test cases, mapping tests to requirements, and conducting tests to demonstrate system interoperability. Ms. Beltz assisted with conducting formal test events to ensure that Net-Ready Key Performance Parameters (KPPs) were met. Her software background and knowledge of predecessor systems provided her with an in-depth knowledge of the operational environment and end-to-end data flows that proved to be indispensable and has made Ms. Beltz the JITC “go to person” for providing technical insights into testing methods and strategies. Ms. Beltz has also written Test and Evaluation Master Plans (TEMPs), participated in or led Developmental Test and Evaluations (DT&E), led Operational Test and Evaluation (OT&E), and has provided testing results and insights to questions being discussed during the Operational Test Readiness Review (OTRR) and Operational Assessment Reviews (OA).
